The "bee car" to avoid collisions
As part of the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired, this time, by nature, and in particular by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, taking as an example the flight of bees, knows how to avoid accidents.
It is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, or the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research of the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Director General of Public Relations for Brand Management Technology and Research and Development, the BR23C is an extension of the Security Shield of four areas produced by Nissan.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the vehicles of the manufacturer.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing are the bee-composed eyes, able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees, and that allow the insect to fly without interruption in its personal space.
To recreate this visual functionality, engineers have developed what they have defined as a localization laser (Laser Range Finder).
This mechanism detects the obstacles in front of the BR23C for a radius within two meters and with a maximum width of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an on-board microprocessor that immediately, allows to prevent collision.
"When the little robot detects an obstacle, it imitates the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning on the wheels at right angles or greater to avoid collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate upwards or downwards, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can turn and not by exploiting endless directions and ways like bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid collisions.
"This device just needs to process the information every few seconds, and act from this data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of previe maneuvers, so it can work without interruption and with only a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, nor mega."
It is the first step towards the development of new technologies for the instantaneous prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the type with lithium ions.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of units with a GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to destination avoiding obstacles in the route.
