Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow her to differentiate her actions by passing them under the control of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with the MUFG also confirms how the current financial crisis forces Wall Street's biggest names to adopt a much more prudent attitude than they had previously assumed.
The modalities defined Monday also show that in the last days the agreement has been modified: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced the sale of 20% of its shares to the Japanese giant for a sum of 8.5 billion dollars.
"A week ago, in Tokyo, Toshihide Mizuno, executive director of the MUFG, explained: "We thought that our share would be exclusively made up of ordinary shares.
But considering the current situation of the world economy and the market, we have chosen to minimize risks and protect ourselves."
On the basis of the weighted average price, MUFG will obtain Morgan Stanley securities at a price below their accounting value of 7%.
And the transaction would result in an investment of at least 20% of equity on a diluted basis."
The agreement provides that the MUFG will be able to convert in one year half of its preferential securities into ordinary shares if, during a given period, the latter were traded more than 50% below the conversion price fixed, or about 47 dollars.
Morgan Stanley assures her that the capital provided by MUFG would allow her to seize investment opportunities, strengthen her balance sheet and increase her liquidity.
A spokesman for the group, however, refused to give details of the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After the investment of MUFG, Morgan Stanley should therefore set a Tier One solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in the sector.
