Rafael Correa à Quito, let's go.
To establish the republic on a socialism right in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the draft of a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished since, according to official results, 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, on a basis of votes of 80%.
According to these results, the "no" were 28%, while 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% white cards.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it should get half of the votes, plus one.
On Sunday, two polls carried out at the exit of the polling stations and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced an overwhelming victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed on the night between Sunday and Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The "Constitution triumphed gloriously", he assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians in the guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The poll, which took place calmly according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OEA), was based on a text of 444 points to consolidate the "new socialism" defended by the President.
This draft Constitution consecrates the state's power over the economy, reserving it the "planning of development" of a country that lives essentially from the oil extraction carried out by large foreign companies and consequently of their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also grants more power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive four-year mandates, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced its intention to exploit this amendment and to re-apply its application for a new term of office in February 2009.
The Constitution also affirms the gratuitousness of health and education services, which the President began to promote in this country of 13,9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American drug operations.
The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched an assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight escorts seized ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held prisoners in the desert for ten days were reported Monday afternoon, safe and sound, in the Egyptian capital.
In the morning, they had been freed in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently in shape, the hostages arrived at the Almaza military base, near Cairo International Airport, around 3:30 p.m., aboard a special plane.
On board a helicopter, they were transferred immediately, without being able to issue any press interview, to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for analysis.
They enjoy "good health" and no ransom has been paid "to the kidnappers", said on the airstrip the Egyptian Minister of Tourism, Zoheir Garanna.
Kidnapped on September 19 during a safari in 4x4 at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptous, the safari organizing agency.
An Egyptian security officer said that 30 members of the special forces, on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night, just before dawn.
"There have been gunshots, half of the kidnappers have been killed, while the others have fled," said the person responsible who requested anonymity.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "flash" unit were sent to Sudan, where they would support German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of Italian secret agents and special forces.
We must admit that if we have achieved this result, it has been thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, the special forces," he said, without adding any more details.
He also denied the payment of a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese patrol army claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle on board which the kidnappers were on and killed six of them, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and captured two of them.
According to the army, the kidnappers are linked to a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement, (SLA_U), immediately denied by the latter.
Letters - The silent majority of culture
On the front page there is a debate on the financing of culture on which the current election campaign is focused.
So much the better.
But part of our cultural life always remains in the shadows.
Who will decide to denounce the miserable sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historical places that are starving?
Which politician will dare remind the federal government that he is neglecting monuments and buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government is paying three and a half million euros for the only restoration of Chinon Castle in the Loire Valley?
With our American neighbours, it is the Constitution that states that heritage protection is part of national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, by every political authority and by every government department, and all this by mutual agreement.
In Québec, at the Federation of Historical Societies of Québec, there are at least 40 000 volunteers who, grouped into 211 companies for the preservation of historical, genealogical, archives and assets preserve, with little money, private archives and archaeological sites.
It is they who, often, defend our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when real estate entrepreneurs and decision-making bodies attack our forgotten remains and cemeteries with their bulldozers.
When will the right space be reserved for history and heritage?
Benelux Governments Nationalise Part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank, Fortis, which was first in difficulty in Europe due to the crisis in the US credit market, through partial nationalisation: the three nations will provide EUR 11.2 billion to the financial institution - insurance with interest also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level on the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the face of the difficulties facing the international financial market for more than a year is that of the Fortis bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard may constitute a precedent.
According to the decision taken on Sunday night all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank's share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell some of its interests, including first of all the assets, mainly insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis' actions had begun with a vertical collapse, serious signs of crisis of the institute had then appeared in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too large to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank's shares on Friday fell by almost 12%, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares has decreased by more than two thirds.
Considering the current stock prices the entire capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the bank's managers this value is not real.
The company summit imputes the collapse of Fortis shares to the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US $700 billion plan.
On Monday the title slowly resumed to rise.
Friday Filip Dierckx was appointed new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has presented themselves with a worthy offer.
The Belgian Government had previously assured investors that they should not fear losing money.
There was no panic among the bank's customers, the branches were not attacked.
Fortis owns its own subsidiaries in Hungary and has also acquired leasing companies.
The fox in the henhouse
In America insurers on life and health, based on people's medical purchasing data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program according to which the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the henhouse to the fox" - writes the Washington Post citing Richard Dick author of the program to follow the prescriptions of medicines.
Insurance companies shall make the insurance fee and the amount due in the event of claims subject to the health status of the customer and if they consider the risk to be too high they shall not take out the insurance.
A long time ago, the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the test had been completed.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: according to the customer's identification code you can easily get information from pharmacies on which medicines you have purchased in the last year and a half and from this the program shows which diseases you suffer and what health conditions you find.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol reducers, this means that the level of fat in your blood is basically incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
On the market there are several versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, so in addition to paper work there is not much left, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons, some medicines are usable for several purposes, e.g. some compounds can be used against migraines or hot flushes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the point of view of insurance - commercial, is as a factor of increase risk, the first two are not.
For the request and data processing have formed separate societies and these, before obtaining from pharmacies the necessary information, ask for the approval of the patient.
Now the authorities are forcing them to do so even though they have not yet imposed fines for negligence.
Some firms have recently also developed the results of laboratory tests and link them to the data of drug consumption in order to provide a more precise picture of the health of patients.
More and more companies have access to data and, in parallel, the control of use will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate law on privacy but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of the Congress there is a bill that gives the supervisory authorities control powers to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that connects the forwarding data with the approval expressed by the person concerned.
Another question is that the person concerned cannot deny approval because otherwise insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the chickens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
