European Union and India double trade
Given that the European Union and India are partners that trade in particular with each other, the agenda of the ninth summit meeting was also dominated by this issue, as well as all other global problems.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit which will deal primarily with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognises that India is becoming a great democratic power to which more voice should be given in international affairs, but the member countries have not yet been able to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So we did not insist on this issue in the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseilles.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as President-in-Office of the Union, José Manuel Barroso, Chairman of the Commission and Javier Solana, High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received the Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double in five years, i.e. to increase trade to EUR 100 billion.
Given that trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not too ambitious.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements, so air traffic can also start in the future.
India would like to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the deal.
The objective is to balance because while the EU is India's first trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the EU's partners.
The summit paid attention to global affairs.
To the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and to terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms on both sides, and called for the convening of a UN conference.
They called for the conclusion of the Doha Trade Round, although both sides played a role in the failure of this.
The EU has confirmed that it remains in the energy and climate programme, i.e. it would like to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees with this, as does the fact that a global pact should be concluded at the climate conference scheduled for next year and greenhouse gas production reduced by 50% by 2050.
They also want to curb the rise in food prices and have supported the convening of an international meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister will now travel to the French capital where at a bilateral meeting he is preparing to sign a treaty on the peaceful use of atomic energy.
