Steve Fossett's plane was found, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of Steve Fossett's plane, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, was found.
The wreckage was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the aircraft, however, there were no human remains.
The sheriff of Madeira County, John Anderson, dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is exactly what Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff therefore pointed out that no human remains were found either in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was given for dead in February.
The U.S. Office for Transport Safety (Ntsb) reported that a team of investigators was sent a few hours after the wreck was seen, which then identified the device: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, missing from September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, again in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal belongings were found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents named Fossett, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's research was interrupted a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire had gained a place in history thanks to a long series of primates.
In 2002, on the sixth attempt, he became the first man to complete the world tour on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world without a stop.
Among his many records, he also flew at 15,445 meters high, above the Andes, but with a copilot.
